\begin_layout Standard
For tables,
 the following points are particularly important:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Related numerical values are aligned vertically under one another,
 even if placing them side by side saves space.
 Vertically aligned numbers are easier to compare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Numerical values are aligned vertically at the decimal point.
 If the number does not contain a decimal point,
 it is aligned where the decimal point would be (after the last digit).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The unit is placed either in the column header or after each numerical value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The table title (caption) is placed above the table,
 not below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tables are explained in the text.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Very large tables containing measured or calculated values are often better presented as graphs.
\end_layout

